  SQL provides several isolation guarantees by default, which are designed to ensure that transactions are executed in a way that minimizes the risk of data inconsistencies. Here are the main isolation guarantees provided by SQL:
  
  1. **Serializable Isolation**:
     - This is the highest level of isolation guarantee provided by SQL. In this mode, SQL guarantees that transactions will be executed in the order they were started, and any changes made by one transaction will be visible to other transactions only after the transaction has completed.
     - This mode is the most restrictive and can lead to slower execution times because it requires all transactions to wait for each other.
  
  2. **Read Committed Isolation**:
     - This is the most common isolation level provided by SQL. In this mode, SQL guarantees that changes made by one transaction are visible to other transactions only after the transaction has completed.
     - This mode is the most restrictive and can lead to slower execution times because it requires all transactions to wait for each other.
  
  3. **Repeatable Read Isolation**:
     - This mode guarantees that a transaction will see the same data values for a given query in each execution, even if the data is changed by other transactions between the executions.
     - This mode is also the most restrictive and can lead to slower execution times because it requires all transactions to wait for each other.
  
