  During a lossy decomposition, the original relation R is modified by inserting a set of tuples r' into it. The new value of v can be computed as:
  
  v' = σ θ (r')
  
  where σ θ (r') represents the projection of R onto the attribute set θ.
  
  Similarly, if R is modified by deleting a set of tuples d' from it, the new value of v can be computed as:
  
  v' = σ θ (r' - d')
  
  where σ θ (r' - d') represents the projection of R minus the tuples in d' onto the attribute set θ.
  
  The reason for this is that deleting a tuple from R can affect the projection of R onto the attribute set θ, but it does not remove all occurrences of the tuple. The remaining occurrences of the tuple are still present in the projection, but they are counted as separate occurrences. This is why the projection of R minus the tuples in d' is used instead of simply deleting the tuples from R.
